The Plant does not require its employees to participate in conducting offensive-type emergency response activities under the HAZWOPER standard; a Non-responding Facility Policy has been adopted.  In the event of an ammonia emergency, the response is to follow the procedures in the Equipment SOP's and the California Hazardous Material Business Plan.  The overall procedure is to shutdown when and where appropriate and safe, evacuate, and notify the local response agencies and WPS (technical support).  Plant employees are to implement hazard communications, provide for the safety of visitors and report to the established Evacuation Staging Area(s) for a head count. Emergency response is coordinated with the County of Monterey Health Department/CUPA and local Fire Department.  Coastal Cooling has verified it is included in the Monterey County Area Emergency Plan. 
   
6.	Planned changes to improve safety

The primary mechanisms to identify and plan safety improvements include (but are not limited to):
¿	Process Hazard Analysis;
¿	Compliance Audits;
¿	Routine inspections, tests & maintenance (Mechanical Integrity Program);
¿	IIAR Bulletin 109 Inspections (IIAR Minimum Safety Criteria For The Safe Operation Of Ammonia Refrigeration Process);
¿	Coastal Cooling and WPS Internal Inspection Protocols
¿	Incident Investigation

The Programs above may result in recommendations ranging from capital improvements to routine maintenance of the plant.  Service calls are established in parallel to identified needs.  

Current planned changes to improve safety include the recommendations identified in the most recent Process Hazard Analyses, which were conducted by experienced teams on 3/11/2016 (MACS&trade; Expansion).  A summary of improvements includes engineering, mechanical, and administrative changes or upgrades.  Coastal has prepared written itemized lists of the improvements which are to be implemented.  Remaining min
